he French Surrealist leader André Breton, who, after reading Lamantia’s youthful work, hailed him as a "voice that rises once in a hundred years." Later, Lamantia went "on the road" with Jack Kerouac and shared the stage with Allen Ginsberg at the famous Six Gallery reading in San Francisco, where Ginsburg first read "Howl." Throughout his life, Lamantia sought to extend and renew the visionary tradition of Romanticism in a distinctly American vernacular, drawing on mystical lore and drug experience in the process. The Collected Poems gathers not only his published work but also an extensive selection of unpublished or uncollected work; the editors have also provided a biographical introduction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literature. 0aAmerican poetryy20th century. 0aAmerican poetry. 0aPoetry. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  a20th century poets.  aamerican poetry.  aamerican poets.  aamerican vernacular.  abeat generation.  abeat.  abiographical introduction.  acollected poems.  acreative forces.  afrench surrealism.  ahumanity.  ajoycean stream.  alifetime.  alifework.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary.  amystical lore.  apoetry.  apostwar generation.  aretrospective.  aromanticism.  asan francisco.  asix gallery reading.  aspiritual quest.  asub surrealism.  asurrealism.  asurrealist leader.  asurrealist movements.  aunited states.  avisionary tradition.1 aCaples, Garrett, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFama, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoron, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPeters, Nancy Joyce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Californ